From childhood's hour I have not been a pilgrim of the common dawn;
I walked with ravens through gardens where moonlight bruised the trembling lawn.
While other children chased the cricket across the jovial, humming green,
I traced the thunder’s hidden wicket and drank the dusk unseen.
Their laughter rose like cider foam, mine echoed hollow, iron, thin;
I hoarded shadows in my bones and kept the wolves within.
Yet do not name me sorrow’s heir, nor weld my face to gloom;
I grew a lantern from my fear, a library from tombs.
Now when the village candles sleep, I rouse the starlight choir;
My pulse becomes the mountain’s keep, my breath, nocturnal fire.
I learned that darkness is a brush that paints the spirit bright;
Without its velvet hush no color courts the light.
Remember, dawn is merely dusk turned inside out by hope;
The secret is to trust the husk and still release the trope.
So walk with me beyond the gate, where difference begins;
We’ll write our names in restless slate and crown our quiet sins.

Blessed be Thou for all the joy that threads the hush of matins’ air,
spiraling like incense through the rafters of a drowsy, dreaming choir;
for the saffron kiss that dawn bestows upon the trembling cedar boughs,
and for the echoing psalm inside my pulse that keeps the dark at bay.
Blessed be Thou for the hush between two heartbeats when the world tilts
into wonder; for the silver taste of water shared from cupped, rough hands;
for bread still warm, steam curling like a quiet promise around the crust;
for every tear collected in Thy palm and pressed, alchemized, to laughter.
Blessed be Thou for the swallows’ circling script that teaches breath to write;
for a child’s question: Why does light forgive the night?—and the silence after;
for rivers that refuse straight lines, proclaiming pilgrimage as praise;
for tremors of desire that shatter stone and seed green mercies.
Blessed be Thou for crow’s-wing midnight, for harvest noon, for all spectra
between; for the fluted bones of reeds that remember wind; for mercy that
outpaces regret; for crimson berries shining against frost like rubies of refusal.
And blessed, thrice blessed, be Thou for letting this fragile tongue lift
its small hosannah, learning to say yes to every radiant breath.

Prelude in Mist:
I walk a midnight avenue of shuttered stalls and neon ghosts;
In every pane of darkened glass a silhouette unfolds,
hand curled like a question, lips mouthing a single phrase: everyone has a fear.

Sonnet:
Everyone has a fear, though masks may smile—
A candle trembling in a velvet room;
A sudden footstep on a distant tile;
The hush that swells into impending doom.
The scholar dreads a page he cannot read,
The sailor, shoreless blue without a star;
The monarch, rust corroding helm and steed;
The child, the dark behind a half-closed door.
Yet fear, twin sibling to our pulse and breath,
Reminds the blood to race, the limbs to brace;
It prunes the reckless blossom, wards off death,
And sets adrenaline upon its chase.
So let the tremor dance within your wrist;
It proves the fragile miracle exists.

Coda:
Morning unlocks its copper-gilded gates.
I exhale the night, but the pulse remains—
a small, bright animal pacing its cage.

Ballad of the Northern Light:
A keeper alone in a cliff-top tower trimmed the lantern glass;
Storm clouds bruised the evening sky, waves shook the iron mass.
He feared not wind nor crash of foam—those hymns were old and clear;
But hush—the darkest dread he kept was silence in the gear.

For should the clockwork stutter, ships would founder on the reef;
He pictured splintered masts and heard imagined mothers’ grief.
So nightly, with a wrench in hand, he listened to each tick,
Feeling the pulse of brass and cog like stitches in the quick.

One winter night the storm surpassed all stories sailors tell;
Lightning speared the weather vane, the tower cracked its shell.
The lantern faltered—gears half-stalled, the lens began to fade;
The keeper’s knuckles whitened, yet he would not be swayed.

He wedged his fear beneath the beam and cranked the wheel once more;
Light roared out like sunrise fire, engraving every shore.

At dawn the sea lay glassy calm, gulls stitched the silver air;
He slept against the railing, dreamless, honest, bare.

So mark this truth when tempests rise and trembling hands appear:
A heart that beats for something else still beats beside its fear.

I had eight birds hatched in one nest up in the rafters of the mill;
They sang above the grinding stones, a bright, unruly trill.
The millers boy took count each dawn, his ledger smudged with flour,
And swore that eight was lucky, for it matches fortunes hour.
I fed them seeds of thistle down and wheat from broken sacks;
They rode the breath of turning wheels, the dust upon their backs.
When river floods came roaring in and timber groaned with fear,
The fledglings bobbed upon the air like lanterns, brave and clear.
The water gnawed the lower beams, the stones went silent, cold;
I huddled under dripping eaves to watch the night unfold.
At dawn the river shrank away, its hunger finally spent;
The mill lay broken, but the nest still crowned the roofs descent.
Eight birds alit along the ridge, their chorus full of spark;
I swear they hauled the sun itself across the sullen dark.
Now when the millstones ghost still turns inside each dream I keep,
I hear those eight wings beating time against the rivers sleep.

Awake, the rails repeat a silver prayer,
their measured echo stitching moving parts;
you can hear the excitement start to linger.
Night folds its tents and leaves the platform bare,
while doves of fog lift, startled by the sparks;
awake, the rails repeat a silver prayer.
Commuters’ coats, like banners in cold air,
announce ambitions, break the hush in shards;
you can hear the excitement start to linger.
Rhythmic as breath, the wheels confess and swear
that every mile will loosen welded bars;
awake, the rails repeat a silver prayer.
Past barns and rivers, through the orchard glare
of rising sun, the engine plucks its stars;
you can hear the excitement start to linger.
It sings of distance ripe for bold affair,
of hidden roads, unmapped peculiar arts;
awake, the rails repeat a silver prayer,
you can hear the excitement start to linger.

I always see to it the circle closes tight,
 that endings find the doors they thought were lost;
 a lantern curtseys to the fleeing night.

 When plans unravel, blown like paper kites,
 I tie their ribbons, seal the fraying floss;
 I always see to it the circle closes tight.

 A friendship drops its feathers mid-flight,
 I sweep them up, stitch wings at any cost;
 my lantern curtseys to the fleeing night.

 If vows grow hoarse from years of silent fight,
 I oil each consonant, relearn the gloss;
 I always see to it the circle closes tight.

 Even the moon can misplace her own light;
 I polish craters, temper lunar frost;
 my lantern curtseys to the fleeing night.

 Should I be absent, clocks would shiver in fright,
 roads forget their purpose, seasons get lost;
 so I always see to it the circle closes tight,
 and the lantern keeps curtseying to the fleeing night.

Shall I, wasting in despair, unthread the moonlit skein of night,
And barter hours for hollow sighs that tremble like a candle’s light?
Shall I permit my heart to fade as petals drop from frost-kissed bloom,
While clocks in secret corridors insist on chiseling my doom?
No—let despair be but a gust that bends yet breaks no rooted bough;
I’ll raise a cup of restless dawn and drink the fierce, unpromised now.
For every tear that stains the dark, a seed of wonder splits the soil;
For every fractured, aching dream, new constellations spin and coil.
The hurt becomes horizon, wide, where golden sorrow melts to rose;
I walk the rim of anguish brief, then cross to where the wild light grows.
From broken mirrors let me build a palace for the raven’s song;
From splintered hopes a violin to teach the silent stars their throng.
So shall I, wasting in despair, be sculptor of the shattered grave;
Transmuting grief to fusional fire, I find the strength I never gave.
Therefore, though shadows claw my sleeve, I stride into tomorrow’s flare;
For wasted I am not, who dares to spin new worlds from midnight air.
